1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:08,500
(1 John 3:1): 'See what kind of love the Father has given to us, that we should be called children of God—and so we are.

2
00:00:08,450 --> 00:00:15,825
It must be understood that this is all the same thing: knowing God and being known by God, and seeing God and being seen by God.

3
00:00:15,825 --> 00:00:19,537
We know God and see him because he makes us know and see.

4
00:00:19,537 --> 00:00:29,400
Even as the luminous air is not distinguishable from its luminant, for it is luminous with what illumines it, so do we know by being known, by his making us conscious.

5
00:00:29,400 --> 00:00:32,012
Christ said, ‘Again ye shall see me.

6
00:00:32,012 --> 00:00:41,712
That is to say: by making you see I make you see me, whereat ‘your heart shall rejoice,’ rejoice in the vision and knowledge of God, and ‘your joy no man taketh from you.

7
00:00:41,712 --> 00:00:49,250
St. John says: ‘Behold what manner of charity the Father hath bestowed upon us that we should be called and should be the sons of God.

8
00:00:49,250 --> 00:00:52,212
He says not only ‘should be called’ but ‘should be.

9
00:00:52,212 --> 00:01:01,912
Now I maintain that we can no more be wise without wisdom than Son without the filial nature of God’s Son: without having the very same nature as the Son of God himself.

10
00:01:01,912 --> 00:01:04,150
Wouldst thou be the Son of God?

11
00:01:04,150 --> 00:01:08,550
Thou canst not, without having the same nature as the Son of God.

12
00:01:08,550 --> 00:01:19,287
But this is hidden from us here, as it is written, ‘Beloved, now we are God’s sons (and it doth not yet appear what we shall be), but we know that he is our exemplar and we shall be like him.

13
00:01:19,287 --> 00:01:27,225
That is, the same as he is: same life and enjoyment and understanding: exactly the same as he is, when we see him as God.

14
00:01:27,225 --> 00:01:35,650
I say, God cannot make me the Son of God without I have the nature of God’s Son, any more than God can make me wise without my having wisdom.

15
00:01:35,650 --> 00:01:44,250
Though we are God’s sons, we do not realize it yet: ‘it doth not yet appear’ to us, but this much we do know, he says, ‘we shall be like him.

16
00:01:44,250 --> 00:01:48,987
Sundry things in our souls overlay this knowledge and conceal it from us.

17
00:01:48,987 --> 00:02:06,187
The soul has something in her, a spark of intellect, that never dies; and in this spark, as at the apex of the mind, we place the paradigm of the soul; and there is also in our souls knowledge of externals, sensible and rational perception, present there as images and words which obscure it from us.

18
00:02:06,187 --> 00:02:07,925
How are we God’s sons?

19
00:02:07,925 --> 00:02:10,087
By having one nature with him.

20
00:02:10,087 --> 00:02:15,950
But any realization of this, of being God’s sons, is subjective not objective knowledge.

21
00:02:15,950 --> 00:02:20,087
The inner consciousness strikes down to the very essence of the soul.

22
00:02:20,087 --> 00:02:36,187
Not that it is the soul itself, but it is rooted there and is in a measure the life of the soul, her intellectual life, the life, that is, wherein a man is born God’s Son, born into the eternal life, for this knowledge is a-temporal, unextended, without here and without now.

23
00:02:36,187 --> 00:02:42,337
In this life all things are the same thing and all things common; all things are all in all and all atoned.

24
00:02:42,337 --> 00:02:44,512
I will give you an illustration.

25
00:02:44,512 --> 00:02:49,300
In the body the members are united so that eye belongs to foot and foot to eye.

26
00:02:49,300 --> 00:02:56,675
Could the foot speak, it would declare that the eye seems rather in the foot than in the head, and the eye would say the same the other way about.

27
00:02:56,675 --> 00:03:05,725
Accordingly, I trow that the grace which is in Mary is really more an angel’s and is more in him (yet being in Mary) than if it were in him or in the saints.

28
00:03:05,725 --> 00:03:13,537
For everything that Mary has belongs to every saint, so the grace in Mary is his own and he enjoys it more than if it really were in him.

29
00:03:13,708 --> 00:03:19,108
But such a simile is too gross and carnal, depending as it does on bodily imagery.

30
00:03:19,058 --> 00:03:23,445
I will give you another, therefore, more subtle, less material.

31
00:03:23,445 --> 00:03:27,683
I assert that in heaven all is in all and all one and all ours.

32
00:03:27,683 --> 00:03:36,633
The grace our Lady has exists in me (when I am yonder), not as welling up in and flowing out of Mary, but as in me as my own and not of foreign origin.

33
00:03:36,633 --> 00:03:47,220
I contend that there what one has another has, not as from another nor as in another, but in its own self, so that the grace in one is simultaneously in another as his own grace.

34
00:03:47,220 --> 00:03:49,408
Thus spirit is in spirit.

35
00:03:49,408 --> 00:03:59,770
And that is why I say I cannot be the son of God unless I have the very nature the Son of God has there; and that having this same nature makes us the same as he is, we seeing him as God.

36
00:03:59,770 --> 00:04:02,595
But it doth not yet appear what we shall be.

37
00:04:02,595 --> 00:04:12,408
Meaning, I take it, that there is then no like nor different, but: wholly without distinction we are the same in essence and in substance and in nature as he is himself.

38
00:04:12,408 --> 00:04:16,870
This is not apparent now: it will be obvious when we see him as God.

39
00:04:16,870 --> 00:04:29,870
God makes us to know him, and his knowing is his being, and his making me know is the same as my knowing, so his knowing is mine: just as, in the master, what he teaches is the same as, in the pupil, the thing that he is taught.

40
00:04:29,870 --> 00:04:38,795
And because his knowing is mine, and his knowing is his substance and his nature and his essence, it follows that his substance and his nature and his essence are mine.

41
00:04:38,795 --> 00:04:44,620
And his substance, his nature and his essence being mine, therefore I am the Son of God.

42
00:04:44,620 --> 00:04:51,433
Behold, brethren, what manner of love God hath bestowed upon us that we should be called and should be the Son of God!

43
00:04:51,433 --> 00:05:05,920
Mark whereby we are sons of God: by having the same nature as the Son of God.—How can one be the Son of God, or know it, seeing that God is not like anybody?—True, Isaias says, ‘To whom will ye liken God or what likeness will ye compare unto him?

44
00:05:05,920 --> 00:05:11,983
Since it is God’s nature to be not like anyone, we must needs not be so to be the same as he is.

45
00:05:11,983 --> 00:05:22,145
When I contrive to see myself in naught and to see naught in me; when I succeed in rooting up and casting out everything in me, then I am free to pass into the naked being of the soul.

46
00:05:22,145 --> 00:05:31,420
Likes must be ousted ere I can be transplanted into God and be the same as he is: same substance, same essence, same nature and the Son of God.

47
00:05:31,420 --> 00:05:36,895
Once this happens, there is nothing hid in God that is not revealed, that is not mine.

48
00:05:36,895 --> 00:05:41,120
I am wise and mighty just as he is, and one and the same with him.

49
00:05:41,120 --> 00:05:48,370
Then Sion is a true beholder, true Israel, a seer: God, since nothing in the Godhead is concealed from him.

50
00:05:48,370 --> 00:05:50,470
Man is turned into God.

51
00:05:50,470 --> 00:05:59,933
But that nothing may be concealed from me, everything revealed, there must appear in me no like, no image, for no image can show us God’s nature nor his essence.

52
00:05:59,933 --> 00:06:04,645
While there abideth in thee any image or like thou art never the same as God.

53
00:06:04,645 --> 00:06:12,333
To be the same as God there must be nothing in thee, latent or defined, nothing covered in thee that is not discovered and cast out.

54
00:06:12,333 --> 00:06:13,945
Mark what sin is.

55
00:06:13,945 --> 00:06:15,858
It is born of negation.

56
00:06:15,858 --> 00:06:22,345
Negation’s brood must be exterminated in the soul; while there is not in thee thou art not the Son of God.

57
00:06:22,345 --> 00:06:24,995
We weep and lament for want of something.

58
00:06:24,995 --> 00:06:31,833
The minus quantity must go, be cancelled out, if man is to become the Son of God and weep and wail no more.

59
00:06:31,833 --> 00:06:35,608
Man is not wood nor stone: imperfection and naught.

60
00:06:35,608 --> 00:06:41,320
We shall not be like him until this minus is made good and we are all in all as God is all in all.

61
00:06:41,476 --> 00:06:47,526
There are two births of man: one in the world, the other one out of the world and ghostly, in God.

62
00:06:47,476 --> 00:06:50,951
Wouldst know if thy child is born and if he is naked?

63
00:06:50,951 --> 00:06:54,613
Whether, that is to say, thou hast been made God’s Son?

64
00:06:54,613 --> 00:06:59,176
If thy heart is heavy, except for sin, thy child is not born.

65
00:06:59,176 --> 00:07:04,426
In thine anguish thou art not yet mother: thou art in labour and thine hour is nigh.

66
00:07:04,426 --> 00:07:11,663
Doubt not, if thou art travailing for thyself or for thy friend no birth has taken place though birth be close at hand.

67
00:07:11,663 --> 00:07:20,113
The birth is not over till thy heart is free from care: then man has the essence and nature and substance and wisdom and joy and all that God has.

68
00:07:20,113 --> 00:07:25,713
Then the very being of the Son of God is ours and in us and we attain to actual Deity.

69
00:07:25,713 --> 00:07:31,976
Christ says: ‘If any will come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me.

70
00:07:31,976 --> 00:07:36,638
That is: cast away care and let perpetual joy reign in your heart.

71
00:07:36,638 --> 00:07:38,551
Thus the child is born.

72
00:07:38,551 --> 00:07:45,651
And when the child is born in me, the sight of friends, of father, dead there before my eyes will leave my heart untouched.

73
00:07:45,651 --> 00:07:51,826
Were my heart moved thereby the child would not be born in me, though peradventure its nativity is nigh.

74
00:07:51,826 --> 00:07:58,763
I maintain that God and his angels take such keen delight in every act a good man does, that there is no joy like it.

75
00:07:58,763 --> 00:08:08,601
And accordingly, I say, the birth of this child in thee brings thee most keen delight in all good deeds done in this world, thy joy being so continuous as to be never-ending.

76
00:08:08,601 --> 00:08:12,226
Hence the words: ‘Your joy no man taketh from you.

77
00:08:12,226 --> 00:08:16,813
When I am transported into God, then God is mine and all he has.

78
00:08:16,813 --> 00:08:19,426
I am the Lord thy God,’ he says.

79
00:08:19,426 --> 00:08:26,701
Then I have real delight which neither pain nor sorrow can take from me, for then I am installed in God where sorrow has no place.

80
00:08:26,701 --> 00:08:31,638
We shall see that in God is no anger nor sadness, but only love and joy.

81
00:08:31,638 --> 00:08:42,676
Though he seem sometimes to be wrathful with sinners it is not really wrath, it is his kindness, the effect of his great love: ‘Whom he loveth he chasteneth,’ for he is love, the Holy Ghost.

82
00:08:42,676 --> 00:08:46,776
God’s anger springs from love; he chides us with dispassion.

83
00:08:46,776 --> 00:08:52,476
When nothing is grievous or hard, when all is pure joy, then verily thy child is born.

84
00:08:52,476 --> 00:09:00,263
Strive that this child shall be not nascent merely but be born in thee, even as in God his Son is ever being born and is ever born.

85
00:09:00,263 --> 00:09:03,101
May this betide, So help us God.

86
00:09:03,101 --> 00:09:04,013
Amen.
